{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507120"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2604"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2604"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.31,0.2,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2604"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64373"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1502"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is admitted to hospital with sepsis secondary to a diabetic foot infection. He is started on a broad-spectrum antibiotics and his infection improves. However, on day three of the admission, he develops a widespread, erythematous rash with pustules over flexural folds of the axillae, groin and some on his torso. His blood pressure is 132/78 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis (AGEP)","Stevens-Johnson syndrome / toxic epidermal necrolysis","Drug hypersensitivity syndrome","Generalised pustular psoriasis","Neutrophilic dermatoses"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis individual has \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute generalised exanthematous pustulosis\u003C/strong\u003E (AGEP) likely related to the use of a broad spectrum antibiotic, likely piperacillin/tazobactam. AGEP is an uncommon drug eruption characterised by superficial pustules. It is associated with medications in 90% of cases and in most cases due to beta-lactam antibiotics. Less common triggers includes viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rash seen in AGEP is characterised by erythematous areas of skin with pinhead sized pustules; it typically begins in the face and involves flexural folds including axilla or groin before becoming widespread. As a rule, the rash from AGEP occurs within 2-5 days following exposure to the culprit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of AGEP is targeted at removal of the offending agent and offering symptomatic relief through emollients and topical or systemic corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug hypersensitivity syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E may overlap with AGEP, although patients are generally more systemically unwell, experiencing the combination of fever, arthralgia and myalgia with morbiliform rash. Multi-organ failure is present. This syndrome is most commonly associated with anti-epilepsy medications such as carbemazepine, phenytoin and phenobarbital.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESteven-Johnson syndrome / toxic epidermal necrolysis\u003C/strong\u003E (SJS/TEN) is a life-threatening severe form of drug reaction. It induces necrotic skin change that leads to blisters with complete loss of the epidermis. Causes are similar to those of AGEP with antibiotics implicated in 40% of cases. Patients present with SJS/TEN ~7-10 days post exposure to the culprit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised pustular psoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E also presents as a widespread, erythematous pustular rash, which may be triggered acutely by steroid withdrawal, medications such as lithium, aspirin and indomethacin, as well as pregnancy and infection. For this case, it is more likely that the rash is related to antibiotic use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophilic dermatoses \u003C/strong\u003Eincludes conditions such as Sweet syndrome, Pyoderma Gangrenosum. It can present with an acute onset and have clinical features that overlap with AGEP. However, patients with Sweet\u0027s syndrome usually presents with much well-defined erythematous oedematous plaques that have pseudo-vesicular appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta-lactam antibiotics are a common cause of acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis.","Acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis typically presents with a rapid onset of pustular rash following drug exposure."],"references":["Purvis, D 2008, Acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis, DermNet NZ, New Zealand. [Internet]. Accessed on 13 Jan 2025. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/acute-generalised-exanthematous-pustulosis/#:~:text=Acute%20generalised%20exanthematous%20pustulosis%2C%20or,is%20also%20called%20toxic%20pustuloderma","Sidoroff A, Dunant A, Viboud C, Halevy S, Bavinck JN, Naldi L, Mockenhaupt M, Fagot JP, Roujeau JC. Risk factors for acute generalized exanthematous pustulosis (AGEP)-results of a multinational case-control study (EuroSCAR). Br J Dermatol. 2007 Nov;157(5):989-96. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2133.2007.08156.x. Epub 2007 Sep 13. PMID: 17854366. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17854366/","Speeckaert MM, Speeckaert R, Lambert J, Brochez L. Acute generalized exanthematous pustulosis: an overview of the clinical, immunological and diagnostic concepts. Eur J Dermatol. 2010 Jul-Aug;20(4):425-33. doi: 10.1684/ejd.2010.0932. Epub 2010 Jun 14. PMID: 20542841. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20542841/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64373"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2604"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64373"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:26:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T13:27:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2604"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":